text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!MorphosyntacticDiversity]]%0a%0a!Canadian eh%0a%0a:Author: sathyas%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aShort Article detailing the use of 'eh' in Canadian English%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aOne of the common stereotypes about Canadians and their speaking is that their speech is littered with eh's. The Canadian eh is a word added at the end of declarative sentences, and it is similar to saying 'right' or 'don't you' at the end of a sentence. It turns the sentence from a declarative to a conformational often. Here are some examples:%0a%0aYou have a new cat.%0aYou have a new cat, eh?%0aYou have a new cat, right?%0a%0aThis speech phenomena is most commonly found in speakers of central Canada (Toronto). A few studies agree that the use of 'eh' is more prevalent amongst lower class, uneducated, and rural men. It is used in two different positions of a sentence.%0a%0aThe first is at the end of a clause (usually a sentence):%0aYou have a new cat, eh?%0aYou have a new cat eh so make sure you get some catnip.%0a%0aThe second is as a standalone utterance.%0aEh? Can you repeat your cat's name?%0a%0aIt cannot be used within a sentence or clause:%0aYou eh have a new cat?%0a%0aAs stated earlier, the use of eh is often a "conformational" to transform a declarative statement to a "request for confirmation." Hence, phrases like 'don't you' or 'right' in standard English perform the same purpose. Besides the use in questions, 'eh' is also commonly used with imperatives and narratives. The imperative eh replaces phrases such as 'will', 'won't', 'would'. The narrative, or anecdotal, eh is used at the end of a clause within a setence.%0a%0aImperative example:%0aThink about it, won't you?%0aThink about it eh?%0a%0aNarrative example:%0aSo I find this cat, eh, and he tries to bite me, eh.%0a%0a'Eh' is so prevalent within Canadian speech due to the vast amount of use cases. It is used to confirm that the speaker is understanding the narrative. There are a few semantic differences with English translations which allow 'eh' to be used even more often.%0aFor example:%0a%0aI have a new cat, eh?%0aI have a new cat, don't I?%0aI have a new cat, right?%0a%0aBoth sentences are grammatically correct, however the standard English dialect does not make semantic sense. The Canadian 'eh' is used solely as confirm the listener's understanding and does not suggest the speaker does not know they have a cat.%0a%0aThe only restriction for using 'eh' is that the assumptions made are generally weak. It cannot be used for imperatives. For example, a army general cannot say:%0a%0a"Forward march, eh!"%0a%0aThere is a strong implied assumption that the general's troops will follow their command, so it does not make semantic sense to add 'eh'.%0a%0a%0aHopefully this can act as a blueprint to help you all speak slightly more Canadian.%0a%0a%0a%0aSource: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/canadian-eh%0aFamily Guy clip of stereotypical eh usage: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-5VTYDOSFIk%0a%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210412-002729-627280#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!This exists in other languages, eh? %0a-> - Thomas_H_K%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aWhile the Canadian 'Eh' is probably the most well-known construction of this type, other languages and English dialects have similar phrases.%0aThese phrases are all categorized as “tag questions,” which the article defines as imperative usage, or as “invariant tags,” when they are used as a general interjection. Most invariant tags can be tag questions, but not vice versa.%0aSome examples of phrases with similar usage are:%0a%0a‘Innit’ in British English.%0a“He can still come to the party innit.” has innit meaning “can’t he?”%0a%0a‘Verdad’ in Spanish. %0a“Entonces, fui a trabajar por la mañana, ¿verdad?” translates to “So, I went to work in the morning, right?” with '¿verdad?' meaning 'right?'%0a%0a‘Nicht wahr’ in German.%0a“as ist Anfängerwissen, nicht wahr?” translates to “I mean, that's basic, isn't it?” with 'nicht wahr?' meaning 'isn't it?'  %0a%0aSources:%0ahttp://www.bbc.co.uk/voices/yourvoice/conversation3.shtml%0ahttps://context.reverso.net/translation/german-english/nicht+wahr%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210412-002729-627280#%0a#foxbegin 210418-214544-90050#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!It can appear in both matching and contrasting polarity tag questions, eh? %0a-> - Simon_Y%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI thought there is an insteresting grammatical property of the "eh".%0a%0aIn standard English, a tagged question can only exist in certain polarity patterns. [Postitive(P), Negative(N)]%0a%0aa. Oh, you're still here, are you?    (P-P)%0a%0ab. That should be okay, shouldn't it? (P-N)%0a%0ac. He didn't do it, did he?           (N-P)%0a%0ad. *He didn’t do it, didn’t he?      *(N-N)%0a%0aAs you can see, a tag question cannot match the polarity of a negative sentence. However, the "eh" can appear in all of the combinations of polarity.%0a%0aa. Oh, you’re still here, eh?%0a%0ab. That should be okay, eh?%0a%0ac. He didn't do it, eh?%0a%0aAbove examples are all valid.%0a%0aThought this would make an interesting sidenote to the article.%0a%0aRef: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/canadian-eh%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210418-214544-90050#%0a#foxbegin 210424-225048-684380#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!An equivalent in Japanese %0a-> - JacobF%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aIn Japanese, various 'particles' are inserted between words to identify their relationship with one another (on problem set 4, 'ga' 'o' and 'wa' are all examples of particles).%0a%0a%0aThe particle 'ne' (ね) may be appended to a sentence to change its tone to one of asking for confirmation. Interestingly, this almost identically maps to the Canadian Eh, in that they both appear sentence-finally, and both change an assertion into that of a questioning (and they sound a little similar). This works both for positive and negative sentences.%0a%0aFor example,%0a%0a'anata no  tomodachi no namae  wa     Clark desu'%0a  you  pos  friend   pos name  topic  Clark is%0ayour friend's name is clark%0a%0avs%0a%0a%0a'anata no  tomodachi no namae  wa     Clark desu ne'%0a  you  pos  friend   pos name  topic  Clark is   eh%0ayour friend's name is clark, right?%0a%0a%0a(pos is short for possesion)%0a%0a%0aand also%0a%0a'kore   wa  niku ja nai desu' %0a that topic meat   not   is%0a that is not meat%0a%0aversus%0a%0a'kore   wa  niku ja nai desu ne'%0a that topic meat   not   is  eh%0a that is not meat, is it?%0a%0aSource:%0a%0aBanno, Eri, et al. An Integrated Course in Elementary Japanese. The Japan Times, 2011. %0a%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210424-225048-684380#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: E:)%0a(:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity:)%0a
