diff:1618782344:1618520953:=119,151d118%0a%3c #foxbegin 210418-214544-90050#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!It can appear in both matching and contrasting polarity tag questions, eh? %0a%3c -> - Simon_Y%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c I thought there is an insteresting grammatical property of the "eh".%0a%3c %0a%3c In standard English, a tagged question can only exist in certain polarity patterns. [Postitive(P), Negative(N)]%0a%3c %0a%3c a. Oh, you're still here, are you?    (P-P)%0a%3c %0a%3c b. That should be okay, shouldn't it? (P-N)%0a%3c %0a%3c c. He didn't do it, did he?           (N-P)%0a%3c %0a%3c d. *He didn’t do it, didn’t he?      *(N-N)%0a%3c %0a%3c As you can see, a tag question cannot match the polarity of a negative sentence. However, the "eh" can appear in all of the combinations of polarity.%0a%3c %0a%3c a. Oh, you’re still here, eh?%0a%3c %0a%3c b. That should be okay, eh?%0a%3c %0a%3c c. He didn't do it, eh?%0a%3c %0a%3c Above examples are all valid.%0a%3c %0a%3c Thought this would make an interesting sidenote to the article.%0a%3c %0a%3c Ref: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/canadian-eh%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210418-214544-90050#%0a
