diff:1618187246:1617558998:=95,118c95%0a%3c #foxbegin 210412-002729-627280#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!This exists in other languages, eh? %0a%3c -> - Thomas_H_K%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c While the Canadian 'Eh' is probably the most well-known construction of this type, other languages and English dialects have similar phrases.%0a%3c These phrases are all categorized as “tag questions,” which the article defines as imperative usage, or as “invariant tags,” when they are used as a general interjection. Most invariant tags can be tag questions, but not vice versa.%0a%3c Some examples of phrases with similar usage are:%0a%3c %0a%3c ‘Innit’ in British English.%0a%3c “He can still come to the party innit.” has innit meaning “can’t he?”%0a%3c %0a%3c ‘Verdad’ in Spanish. %0a%3c “Entonces, fui a trabajar por la mañana, ¿verdad?” translates to “So, I went to work in the morning, right?” with '¿verdad?' meaning 'right?'%0a%3c %0a%3c ‘Nicht wahr’ in German.%0a%3c “as ist Anfängerwissen, nicht wahr?” translates to “I mean, that's basic, isn't it?” with 'nicht wahr?' meaning 'isn't it?'  %0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c http://www.bbc.co.uk/voices/yourvoice/conversation3.shtml%0a%3c https://context.reverso.net/translation/german-english/nicht+wahr%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210412-002729-627280#%0a---%0a> %0a
