diff:1617558998:1617558998:=1,117d0%0a%3c (:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!MorphosyntacticDiversity]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Canadian eh%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: sathyas%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Short Article detailing the use of 'eh' in Canadian English%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c One of the common stereotypes about Canadians and their speaking is that their speech is littered with eh's. The Canadian eh is a word added at the end of declarative sentences, and it is similar to saying 'right' or 'don't you' at the end of a sentence. It turns the sentence from a declarative to a conformational often. Here are some examples:%0a%3c %0a%3c You have a new cat.%0a%3c You have a new cat, eh?%0a%3c You have a new cat, right?%0a%3c %0a%3c This speech phenomena is most commonly found in speakers of central Canada (Toronto). A few studies agree that the use of 'eh' is more prevalent amongst lower class, uneducated, and rural men. It is used in two different positions of a sentence.%0a%3c %0a%3c The first is at the end of a clause (usually a sentence):%0a%3c You have a new cat, eh?%0a%3c You have a new cat eh so make sure you get some catnip.%0a%3c %0a%3c The second is as a standalone utterance.%0a%3c Eh? Can you repeat your cat's name?%0a%3c %0a%3c It cannot be used within a sentence or clause:%0a%3c You eh have a new cat?%0a%3c %0a%3c As stated earlier, the use of eh is often a "conformational" to transform a declarative statement to a "request for confirmation." Hence, phrases like 'don't you' or 'right' in standard English perform the same purpose. Besides the use in questions, 'eh' is also commonly used with imperatives and narratives. The imperative eh replaces phrases such as 'will', 'won't', 'would'. The narrative, or anecdotal, eh is used at the end of a clause within a setence.%0a%3c %0a%3c Imperative example:%0a%3c Think about it, won't you?%0a%3c Think about it eh?%0a%3c %0a%3c Narrative example:%0a%3c So I find this cat, eh, and he tries to bite me, eh.%0a%3c %0a%3c 'Eh' is so prevalent within Canadian speech due to the vast amount of use cases. It is used to confirm that the speaker is understanding the narrative. There are a few semantic differences with English translations which allow 'eh' to be used even more often.%0a%3c For example:%0a%3c %0a%3c I have a new cat, eh?%0a%3c I have a new cat, don't I?%0a%3c I have a new cat, right?%0a%3c %0a%3c Both sentences are grammatically correct, however the standard English dialect does not make semantic sense. The Canadian 'eh' is used solely as confirm the listener's understanding and does not suggest the speaker does not know they have a cat.%0a%3c %0a%3c The only restriction for using 'eh' is that the assumptions made are generally weak. It cannot be used for imperatives. For example, a army general cannot say:%0a%3c %0a%3c "Forward march, eh!"%0a%3c %0a%3c There is a strong implied assumption that the general's troops will follow their command, so it does not make semantic sense to add 'eh'.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Hopefully this can act as a blueprint to help you all speak slightly more Canadian.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Source: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/canadian-eh%0a%3c Family Guy clip of stereotypical eh usage: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-5VTYDOSFIk%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %2